Q2.List two hormones that act on the distal convolutedtubule of the kidneys and two hormones that act on thecollecting ducts of the kidneys.

Q2.List two hormones that act on the distal convolutedtubule of the kidneys and two hormones that act on thecollecting duct of the kidneys.

DCT: aldosterone, parathyroid hormone, insulin, (couldpossibly accept antidiuretic hormone and angiotensin II)

CD: Natriuretic peptide, antidiuretic hormone, andpossibly aldosterone

Q3. Briefly describe the mechanisms by which peristalsispushes the bolus down the oesophagus.

Q3. Briefly describe the mechanisms by which peristalsispushes the bolus down the oesophagus.

The bolus stretches the smooth muscle. There is areflexive contraction oral to the stretch and a reflexiverelaxation/dilation anal to the stretch. The contractionpropagatesanally.

Figure 25.11

Q4. List in the inputs and outputs of glycolysis,anaerobic fermentation and aerobic respiration.

Q3. List in the inputs and outputs of glycolysis,anaerobic fermentation and aerobic respiration.

Glycolysis splits a glucose molecule into two moleculesof pyruvate.

Anaerobic fermentation reduces pyruvate to lactate.

Aerobic respiration has oxygen and pyruvate as inputs,outputs are carbon dioxide and water.

Q3. List in the inputs and outputs of glycolysis,anaerobic fermentation and aerobic respiration.

Q5. List the hormones involved in the control of maleand female reproductive function.

Q5. List the hormones involved in the control of maleand female reproductive function.

Male: Testosterone, gonadotropin-releasing hormone,follicle-stimulating hormone, luteinising hormone andinhibin.

Female: Oestradiol, progesterone, gonadotropin-releasing hormone, follicle-stimulating hormone,luteinising hormone

Q6. List the three primary germ layers and their majorderivatives.

Q6. List the three primary germ layers and their majorderivatives.

  • Ectoderm
    • Epidermis, hair, nervous system, eyes, ears, glands,epithelia of nose/mouth/anal canal
  • Mesoderm
    • Bones, cartilage, muscle, blood, blood and lymphvessels, epithelium of kidneys and genitals,mesothelium of abdominal and thoracic cavities
  • Endoderm
    • Most mucosal epithelium of digestive and respiratorytracts and bladder, epithelial components of accessoryreproductive and digestive glands, thymus

Q8. Describe the process of glomerular filtration.

Q8. Describe the process of glomerular filtration.

Three physical barriers act as the filter

  • Pores in the endothelium
  • Proteoglycan gel of the basement membrane
  • Silts created by processes of the glomerular capsule

Also, the pressure gradient created by large inflow andsmall outflow.
